Polish Stocks: Enea, Handlowy, KGHM, LPP, Orco, Orlen, Zachodni

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i
-- 
2011-04-04T13:25:54Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-04/polish-stocks-enea-handlowy-kghm-lpp-orco-orlen-zachodni.html
Poland ’s WIG20 Index gained 12.91,
or 0.5 percent, to 2,890.15 at 2:45 p.m. in Warsaw, climbing for
a third day and heading for the highest close since June 2008.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
 Warsaw Stock Exchange  today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Enea SA (ENA)  , Poland’s third-largest power utility,
slumped 1.29 zloty, or 6.1 percent, to 19.81 zloty, heading for
the lowest close since August after the Treasury Ministry
confirmed it had ended talks with Electricite de France SA over
the sale of a majority stake.  Bank Handlowy SA (BHW PW) gained 1.8 zloty, or 1.8 percent,
to 104.5 zloty, heading for the highest close since December
2007. The Polish unit of Citigroup Inc. will replace  Bank
Zachodni WBK SA (BZW)  in the benchmark WIG20 index after the close of
trade on April 5, the Warsaw Stock Exchange said on its website.  Zachodni (BZW PW), in which Banco Santander SA of  Spain ,
bought a 96 percent stake last month, fell 1 zloty, or 0.4
percent, to 226 zloty.  KGHM Polska Miedz SA (KGH)  , the copper producer with the
biggest European mine output, increased for a third day, rising
2.9 zloty, or 1.6 percent, to 187.9 zloty as the price of the
metal advanced.  LPP SA (LPP)  , Poland’s largest clothing retailer, rose
50 zloty, or 2.4 percent, to 2,120 zloty, its third day of
gains. March sales rose 27 percent on the year to about 171
million zloty ($61 million) from a year earlier.  Orco Property Group (OPG)  SA climbed for the first time
in three days in Warsaw trading, increasing 1.21 zloty, or 3.2
percent, to 38.86 zloty. Polish mutual fund ING TFI SA raised
its stake in the property developer to more than 5 percent, Orco
said in a regulatory statement.  PKN Orlen SA (PKN PW), Poland’s biggest oil company, gained
0.65 zloty, or 1.2 percent, to 56.75 zloty.  Grupa Lotos SA (LTS)  , the second-largest refiner, increased 1.07 zloty, or 2.4
percent, to 46.07 zloty. Oil climbed to the highest level in 30
months on speculation that U.S. economic growth may support
demand and a protracted conflict in  Libya  will curtail supply.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pawel Kozlowski in Warsaw 
